Q1. Implement Security Best Practices for Cloud Environments [10M]
GUI Walkthrough: AWS Management Console
1. IAM (Identity & Access Management) – GUI Steps
Enable MFA for Root Account

Step	Action
1	Log into AWS Console as root user
2	Search IAM in the top search bar
3	Click Users → root (or your root email)
4	Select Security credentials tab
5	Next to Assigned MFA device, click Assign MFA device
6	Choose Authenticator app (Google Authenticator / Microsoft Authenticator)
7	Scan QR code with phone app, enter two consecutive OTP codes
8	Click Assign MFA – root account now secured
Create Least-Privilege IAM Role

Step	Action
1	IAM → Roles → Create role
2	Select AWS service → EC2 (for example)
3	Click Next
4	Search and select only: AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess (not full access)
5	Click Next → Role name: EC2-S3-ReadOnly-Role
6	Click Create role
Enforce MFA for All Users

Step	Action
1	IAM → Account settings
2	Under Security, check Require MFA to sign in
3	Click Update
2. S3 Encryption – GUI Steps
Enable Default Encryption on S3 Bucket

Step	Action
1	S3 → Buckets → Click your bucket name
2	Select Properties tab
3	Scroll to Default encryption → Click Edit
4	Select Enable → Choose SSE-S3 (AES-256)
5	Click Save changes
Block Public Access

Step	Action
1	Same bucket → Permissions tab
2	Under Block public access, click Edit
3	Check all 4 boxes:
☑ Block public access to buckets and objects granted through new access control lists (ACLs)
☑ Block public access to buckets and objects granted through any access control lists (ACLs)
☑ Block public access to buckets and objects granted through new public bucket policies
☑ Block public access to buckets and objects granted through any public bucket policies
4	Click Save changes
3. VPC Security – GUI Steps
Create Security Group with Least Privilege

Step	Action
1	VPC → Security Groups → Create security group
2	Name: Web-Server-SG
3	Inbound rules:
Type: HTTPS	Source: 0.0.0.0/0 (if public)
Type: HTTP	Source: 0.0.0.0/0
Type: SSH	Source: Your office IP only (e.g., 203.0.113.0/32)
4	Outbound rules: Keep default (all traffic)
5	Click Create security group
4. Encryption for RDS Databases – GUI Steps
Enable Encryption on New RDS Instance

Step	Action
1	RDS → Create database
2	Choose Standard create
3	Select engine (e.g., MySQL)
4	Under Encryption, check Enable encryption
5	Choose a KMS key (use default AWS managed key)
6	Complete rest of configuration → Click Create database
Enable Encryption on Existing Unencrypted RDS (GUI Workaround)

Step	Action
1	Take a snapshot of the existing database
2	RDS → Snapshots → Select snapshot
3	Click Actions → Copy snapshot
4	Under Encryption, check Enable encryption
5	Restore new encrypted database from encrypted snapshot
6	Migrate traffic → Delete old unencrypted database
Q2. Configure Cloud Monitoring Tools to Track Security Threats [15M]
GUI Walkthrough: AWS CloudTrail, CloudWatch, GuardDuty, Security Hub
1. AWS CloudTrail – Enable API Activity Logging
Step-by-Step GUI:

Step	Action
1	Search CloudTrail in AWS Console
2	Click Trails → Create trail
3	Trail name: Company-Security-Trail
4	Under Apply trail to all regions, select Yes
5	Under Management events, select All
6	Under Data events, select S3 and Lambda (track object-level activity)
7	Create new S3 bucket for logs: company-cloudtrail-logs
8	Click Create trail
2. Amazon GuardDuty – Intelligent Threat Detection
Step-by-Step GUI:

Step	Action
1	Search GuardDuty
2	Click Get started
3	Click Enable GuardDuty
4	Once enabled, click Settings → Configure findings export to S3
5	Review sample findings under Findings tab to see what GuardDuty monitors
Common Findings GuardDuty Detects:

UnauthorizedAccess:EC2/SSHBruteForce

CryptoCurrency:EC2/BitcoinTool.B

Recon:EC2/PortProbeUnprotectedPort

Backdoor:EC2/DenialOfService.Udp

3. Amazon CloudWatch – Configure Alarms
Create CloudWatch Alarm for Unauthorized API Calls

Step	Action
1	CloudWatch → Alarms → All alarms → Create alarm
2	Click Select metric → CloudTrail → Event metrics
3	Select metric: UnauthorizedOperation events
4	Statistic: Sum → Period: 5 minutes
5	Condition: Greater than threshold → 0
6	Configure notification: Create new SNS topic → Email: security@company.com
7	Alarm name: Unauthorized-API-Call-Alert
8	Click Create alarm
Create CloudWatch Alarm for Root Account Usage

Step	Action
1	Same path: CloudWatch → Alarms → Create alarm
2	Select metric: RootAccountUsage
3	Threshold: > 0 for 1 datapoint
4	Notification: Send to security team
5	Name: Root-Account-Activity-Alert
Create Dashboard for Security Metrics

Step	Action
1	CloudWatch → Dashboards → Create dashboard
2	Name: Security-Monitoring
3	Add widgets:
- Line graph: Failed login attempts over time
- Number: Open GuardDuty findings count
- Number: IAM policy changes in last 24h
4	Click Save dashboard
4. AWS Security Hub – Centralized Security View
Step-by-Step GUI:

Step	Action
1	Search Security Hub
2	Click Go to Security Hub → Enable
3	Under Integrations, enable:
☑ GuardDuty
☑ Inspector
☑ Macie
☑ IAM Access Analyzer
4	Go to Insights → Create custom insights for high-severity findings
5	Go to Security standards → Enable CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark
6	Review failing controls and remediate
5. AWS Config – Resource Compliance Monitoring
Step-by-Step GUI:

Step	Action
1	Search AWS Config
2	Click Get started → Set up
3	Under Resources to record, select All resources
4	Under Rules, add managed rules:
- s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited
- s3-bucket-public-write-prohibited
- iam-root-access-key-check
- encrypted-volumes
- restricted-ssh
5	Click Save → Config continuously checks compliance
